How are you gettin' on , and how is the chandlery bis'ness likely to do ? Well , I am so glad to see you . 
It's quite a treat to see you ain't it , Mr. Muzzle ? 'Quite , said Mr. Muzzle . 
'So cheerful he is ! said Sam . 
'In such good spirits ! said Muzzle . 
'And so glad to see us that makes it so much more comfortable , said Sam . 
Mr. Trotter suffered himself to be forced into a chair by the fireside . 
He cast his small eyes , first on Mr. Weller , and then on Mr. Muzzle , but said nothing . 
'The willin ! 'And leave off his evil ways , and set up in the chandlery line arterwards , said the housemaid . 
Do you understand that , Sir ? Here Mr. Muzzle , who had a great notion of his eloquence , in which he imitated his master , paused for a reply . 
But Mr. Trotter made no reply . 
Do you understand that , Sir ? Mr. Muzzle again paused for a reply and again Mr. Trotter disappointed him . 
'Well , then , said Mr. Muzzle , 'I'm very sorry to have to explain myself before ladies , but the urgency of the case will be my excuse . 
The back kitchen's empty , Sir . 
If you will step in there , Sir , Mr. Weller will see fair , and we can have mutual satisfaction till the bell rings . 
At this moment , the bell rang . 
It was an impressive tableau . 
What prevents me ? 'Pride , old fellow , pride , replied Jingle , quite at his ease . 
'I always hated him , added Henrietta . 
'Oh , of course , said Jingle . 
Nupkins , said the elder lady , 'this is not a fit conversation for the servants to overhear . 
Let these wretches be removed . 
'Certainly , my dear , Said Mr , Nupkins . 
